<p><i>Content warning: Maths, with skippable really scary math.</i></p>
<nav>
</nav>
<p>
Assume a gambler is trying to maximise the number of correct prediction on the outcomes of a game repeated several times.
The possible outcomes of the game are the same each time, and each game is independent from the others.
Examples of such a game are a coin toss, a die roll, a lottery, or the roulette.
Assume also that the gambler wants to maximise the number of correct predictions, and the predictions are limited to a single outcome.
We will examine a few common hacks to do so.
</p>
<h3>I hate maths</h3>
<p>
While this topic is deeply tied to maths and its language will be used where possible, the maths will be explained in english and this whole post can be read skipping all the proofs and gory details.
It is also a statistics/probability topic which is one of my weak points because it features hard to parse notations for me.
Hence, I will use the formalism that makes sense to me.
The formalism not be standard, so it is explained in the rest of this section.
</p>
<ul>
<li>The set of reals is <math>&real;</math>; segments of reals are noted inside brackets.</li>
<li>The indicator function (or Iverson bracket if you prefer) is <math>&Iopf;</math>, it takes a logical formula and evaluates to 1 if the formula is true and 0 otherwise.</li>
<li>The universe is <math>&Omega;</math>; it is the set of all possible infinites sequence of games.</li>
<li>A random variables on set <math>X</math> is a function in <math>&Omega->X</math>.</li>
<li>The set of game outcomes is <math>&Oscr;</math>.</li>
<li>The outcome of the nth game is <math>O_n: &Omega->&Oscr;</math>.</li>
<li>The set of events is <math>&Eopf;</math>; it is the set of subsets of the universe <math>&Eopf := &Pscr(&Omega)</math>.</li>
<li>The probability function is <math displaystyle=true>P: &Eopf->@[0,1]$</math>.</li>
<li>The probability of an outcome is <math>p_o ¦ o&in&Oscr;</math>.</li>
<li>When defining random variables, we will shorten the notation by not applying other random variables in their definition as they are always all the same as the argument of the random variable we are defining.</li>
<li>
	Events can be written as logical formulas in places an event would be expected.
	These logical formulas can contain random variables (functions taking a single argument in <math>&Omega;</math>) without their argument specified, and all the arguments are filled with the same implicit value.
	Such a logical formula stands for the set of all <math>&omega;</math> satisfying the formula when it is given as an argument to all the random variables.
	For instance the formula <math>O_1=O_2</math> (the outcome of game 1 is the same as that of game 2) stands for the event <math displaystyle=true>@{&omega&in&Omega ¦ @O_1(&omega)=O_2(&omega)$}$</math> (all the sequence of games where the outcome of the first game is the same as the outcome of the second game).
</li>
</ul>
<h3>Gambler's fallacy</h3>
<p>
The naive, non mathematics versed gamblers usually believe in the following hack:
the most likely outcome is that which occurred the most.
This hack is often called "reverse gambler's fallacy", but for shits and giggles we will call it "gambler's fallacy" here.
This hack isn't necessarily wrong: a consequence of the law of large numbers is that the frequency of an outcome converges to its probability, but this convergence can be slow.<br/>
There are several definition of convergence, but the previous statement holds for all of them.
Here are the definitions from weakest to strongest (meaning each statement is implied by the next ones):
</p>
<details><summary>Common definitions</summary>
	<ul>
	<li>Let <math displaystyle=true>o&in&Oscr;</math> be the outcome we are interesed in.</li>
	<li>We pose therandom variable <math displaystyle=true>S^o_n := &sum_@k=1$^n @&Iopf(O_k=o)$</math> counting the number of successful predictions after game <math><mi>n</mi></math>.</li>
	<li>We pose the random variable <math displaystyle=true>F^o_n := S^o_n/n</math>, the observed frequency after game <math>n</math>.</li>
	</ul>
</details>
<details><summary>Convergence in distribution</summary>
	The frequency of the outcome we are interested in converging in distribution to the probability of that outcome is defined as <math displaystyle=true>&forall;x&in&real-{p_o}, lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n <= x)$ = @&Iopf(p_o <= x)$</math>.<br/>
	The definition captures the "probability of the different values of the frequency we can get after game n" converging to 0 (=we won't get this value) everywhere except at the theoretical probability of the outcome we are interested in when the number of games n reaches to infinity.
	If you were to draw a graph of the probability distribution (vertical axis) of getting a frequency equal to x (x is the horizontal axis) after n games, as n increases the area between the graph and the horizontal line at 0 would go to 0 if you considered any horizontal portion not including the theoretical probability, and to 1 if you include the probability.<br/>
	Please note that the area under the curve for any portion can go to it's limit at its own pace.
	The only requirement (definition of limit) is the area is never bigger than any arbitrarily value we may choose after some number of games which may be different for each horizontal portion of the curve.
</details>
<details><summary>Convergence in probability</summary>
	The frequency of the outcome we are interested in converging in probability to the probability of that outcome is defined as <math displaystyle=true>&forall&epsilon>0, lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(@|F^o_n - p_o|$ < &epsilon)@ = 1</math>.<br/>
	The definition captures the probability of "the frequency being no further from the probability than any arbitrarily small value" converging to 1 (=this will definitely happend).
	If you were to trace the same graph as before and choose any horizontal distance from the probability of the outcome you are interested in, the area between the curve and the horizontal line at 0 will go to 0 as the number of game increases whereas the area within this distance goes to 1.<br/>
	Convergence in probability to a constant is equivalent to convergence in distribution, as I prove below.
</details>
<details><summary>Proof of equivalence between convergence in distribution and convergence in probability to a constant</summary>
	<ul>
	<li>We start by rewriting the Convergence in probability:
		<ul>
		<li><math displaystyle=true>
			0 = 1 - 1 = 1 - lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(@|F^o_n - p_o|$ < &epsilon)$
			= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(@|F^o_n - p_o|$ >= &epsilon)$
			>= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(@|F^o_n - p_o|$ > &epsilon)$
			=_@"case on" F^o_n <= p_o$ lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P({&omega ¦ F^o_n - p_o > &epsilon} &cup {&omega ¦ p_o - F^o_n > &epsilon})$
			= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n - p_o > &epsilon)$ + @P(p_o - F^o_n > &epsilon)$
			>= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ 0 + 0 = 0
		</math></li>
		<li>All of the terms above are in <math>[0, 0]</math> and are therefore all equal to 0.</li>
		<li>Hence we have <math displaystyle=true>&forall&epsilon>0, lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n - p_o > &epsilon)$ + @P(p_o - F^o_n > &epsilon)$ = 0</math>.</li>
		<li>For the sum of those sequences to converge to 0, each individual sequence must converge to 0.</li>
		<li>Thus <math displaystyle=true>&forall&epsilon>0, lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n - p_o > &epsilon)$ = 0 &and lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(p_o - F^o_n > &epsilon)$ = 0</math></li>
		</ul>
	</li>
	<li>Forward direction: let <math>&epsilon>0</math>.
		<ul>
		<li>We have <math displaystyle=true>p_o + &epsilon &in&reals-{p_o}</math> and <math displaystyle=true>p_o - &epsilon &in&reals-{p_o}</math>.</li>
		<li>Therefore by Convergence in distribution we have:
			<ol>
			<li><math displaystyle=true>lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n <= p_o + &epsilon)$ = @&Iopf(p_o <= p_o + &epsilon)$ = 1</math></li>
			<li><math displaystyle=true>lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n <= p_o - &epsilon)$ = @&Iopf(p_o <= p_o - &epsilon)$ = 0</math></li>
			</ol>
		</li>
		<li>Then we do:
			<ul>
			<li><math displaystyle=true>
				0 = 1 - 1 =_1 1 - lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n <= p_o + &epsilon)$
				= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n > p_o + &epsilon)$
				= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n - p_o > &epsilon)$
			</math></li>
			<li><math displaystyle=true>
				0 =_2 lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n <= p_o - &epsilon)$
				= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(-F^o_n > &epsilon - p_o)$ = @P(p_o - F^o_n > &epsilon)$
			</math></li>
			</ul>
		</li>
		<li>Thus we have Convergence in probability.</li>
		</ul>
	</li>
	<li>Backward direction: let <math displaystyle=true>x&in&reals-{p_o}</math>.
		<ul>
		<li>We have <math displaystyle=true>@|x - p_o|$ > 0</math></li>
		<li>Hence Convergence in probability gives us:
			<ol>
			<li><math displaystyle=true>lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n - p_o > @|p_o - x|$)$ = 0</math></li>
			<li><math displaystyle=true>lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(p_o - F^o_n > @|p_o - x|$)$ = 0</math></li>
			</ol>
		</li>
		<li>Then we do a case analysis on <math displaystyle=true>p_o <= x</math>.
			<dl>
			<dt><math displaystyle=true>p_o <= x</math> (<math displaystyle=true>@|p_o - x|$ = x - p_o</math>):</dt>
			<dd><math displaystyle=true>TODO HERE
				@&Iopf(p_o <= x)$ =_@p_o <= x$ 1 = 1 - 0
				=_1 1 - lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n - p_o > x - p_o)$
				= 1 - lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n > x)$ = lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n <= x)$
			</math></dd>
			<dt><math displaystyle=true>p_o > x</math> (<math displaystyle=true>@|p_o - x|$ = p_o - x</math>):</dt>
			<dd><math displaystyle=true>
				@&Iopf(p_o <= x)$ =_@p_o > x$ 0 =_2 lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(p_o - F^o_n > |p_o - x|)$
				=_@p_o > x$ lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(p_o - F^o_n > p_o - x)$
				= lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(-F^o_n > -x)$ = lim_@n->@+&inf$$ @P(F^o_n <= x)$
			</math></dd>
			</dl>
		</li>
		<li>Thus we have Convergence in distribution.</li>
	</ul>
</details>
<details><summary>Almost sure convergence</summary>
	The frequency of the outcome we are interested in converging almost surely to the probability of that outcome is defined as <math displaystyle=true>@P(lim_@n->@+&inf$$ F^o_n = p_o)$ = 1</math>.<br/>
	The definition captures the probability of "the frequency converging to the theoretical probability" being 1 (=will happend).
	It does not mean that you cannot find a sequence of game outcomes that makes the frequence different from the theoretical probability, but that the proportion of all of these sequences ponderated by their probability all together amount to nothing compared to the sequences where the frequency converges to the theoretical probability.<br/>
	Almost sure convergence implies convergence in probability, and we have almost sure convergence of the frequency to the theoretical probability, as I prove below in that order.
</details>
<details><summary>Proof of almost sure convergence implies convergence in probability</summary>
	<li>
	</li>
</details>
