<details><summary>Convergence speed</summary>
</details>
<p>
While these are nice theoretical results, they are unfortunately only theoretical because of limits.
Limits, which means trends at the infinity, or after an arbitrarily big number that may aswell be infinity, are never reached in practice.
In general, calling the outcome with the maximal theoretical probability is better, especially when the frequency didn't have enough time to converge in order to get an idea of the most likely outcome.
To get a general idea of when the probability may not be a good estimate, let's dive into how to get some practical numbers after any number of games you might consider realistic.
</p>
<details><summary>Formula for practical numbers</summary>
</details>
